<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Letter</div>
<div class="nbunit" id="7Jun1926"><font color="red">7 June 1926</font> <i>Letters I</i> (to Harriet Weaver): I hope you received <b><font face="wake">D</font></b>abcd. I shall be writing to hear how you like it &mdash; if you like it. While reading it could you make a complete list of words misspelt. Some, of course, are intentional, most, but there must be others overlooked by my dim sight. Will you let me know if the &lsquo;plot&rsquo; begins to emerge from it at all? Between the close of <font face="wake">A</font> at nightfall and <b><font face="wake">D</font></b>a there are three or four other episodes, the children&apos;s games, night studies, a scene in the &lsquo;public&rsquo;, and a &lsquo;lights out in the village&rsquo;. Have you finished <i>Saint Patrice</i>? If so, I should like you to read St John Irvine&apos;s [Ervine&apos;s] <i>Life of Parnell</i> to begin with. It is not good but you ought to know some of the facts. For instance the word &lsquo;hesitency&rsquo;. Irishmen usually remember the Piggott trial by this catchword. I shall send you B&eacute;dier&apos;s <i>Tristan et Iseult</i> as this too you ought to read. Cain and Co., Swift etc and the &lsquo;other fellow&rsquo; I shall leave to your own interpretative discernment. After my somewhat cloudy interview with Lewis, as I told you, I saw Pound </div>
